Yes, I think it has to be done in an orderly fashion.
There's procedure and machinery that should be in place in all the colleges and universities for students, a mechanism for them to protest.
Yes, they're the consumers, and if there's something that
they think ought to be changed, ought to be a way provided for them to force those complaints.
And, of course, this is what the student deans are supposed to do.
That's a part of the function is to look after the interests of the students.
And a student ought to be able to go to the dean's office
a staff member of the dean's staff with a complaint, and there ought to be a mechanism for addressing it.
In some instances, it can get turned away and said, don't worry about that.
But if the staff members are doing the job, they're listening.
But of course, the activist movement, the demonstrations
They were taking a rather radical way procedure for getting themselves hurt, but it was probably the only mechanism they had.
So I think it caused universities to stop and take notice and see what changes they need to make to provide the freedoms
that can be accorded to students within the university structure.
And there are many rules and regulations that get on the books and just stay there and stay there and stay there.
If somebody doesn't come along and question them, protest them.
And of course the
labor unions used strike.
When they're not getting their way, they'd walk off the job and strike.
Of course, we know some of the ills that have befallen the business and labor as a result of that, but that's another topic.
But yes, the students have a right, a right to protest.
Some of the protests resulted in violence, but not very much of it on the university campus.
There was very little violence.
There was some, and the students' organization could invite whomever they wanted to to come and speak.
We had Abby Hoffman on the campus, and that was a big gathering.

and lots of people there, and this was, I'm supposing that this may well have been sponsored by the Students for the Democratic Society, I'm not sure, but then Stokely Carmichael came to the campus, and these were pretty tense times when we'd have the large gathering, and of course one of my concerns, and I expressed it, so someone finally gave me an answer that satisfied me,
I was saying that the trouble with these big gatherings on the campus, you don't know whether you're looking at students or non-students.
Some of the people that get there are maybe from across the country or east coast to the west coast and all around.
And you don't know what they may be bringing to the campus and encouraging the students to do.
And I said that, blessed that, several times.
And I remember I started to do it.
looked at him and said, the students know whether they're students or not.
They know who's on the campus.
And that was a little bit comforting.
Mickey Leland, an activist from Houston, was on the campus several times.
And he addressed campus groups on the campus and he was
active in the Students for a Democratic Society causes on our campus.
But I think the students have a right to protest.
They have a right to hear whether they want to hear.

Al Kauff was on the campus one time, you know, he's the creator of Little Abner, and he made a speech to the students at the student center, and he said having the students run the university was like having the inmates run the asylum.
He wasn't very strong student government, student running the university.

I think that, from my perspective, that many of the people from the Regents down through the administration down to our staff level, I think many of them saw the need for some changes that were being pointed out by the protest movement.
And the changes have been made.
And I think it is a better climate.
and protects all the students' rights better.
And of course what happens is many times the activists, the protesters, have a pretty narrow focus and it doesn't include the needs of all the students, but most of them
broad enough to be good causes.
Okay.
Okay, could discuss in loco parentis on the campus and Well, that's ait'd take a long time to discuss it much.
I guess traditionally and historically, our parents sent their students to the colleges and universities
with the expectation that they would be looked after, they would be counseled, they would be required to do certain things.
And so the tradition grew up that school officials, college and university officials, were going to take the place of the para when they left home.
They were going to monitor their conduct, they were going to
discipline them when they were out of line.
They were going to send reports back home and let them know how Johnny and Mary were doing.
But in the climate that existed in the 60s and 70s, the students didn't want the university to be the papa and the mama.
They didn't want them to
serve a surrogate role of the parent.
And so the university, for several reasons, got out of the supervision of off-campus housing.
The fraternities and sororities were moved off of the campus.
And just in general,
The life of the student when they walked on the campus was the regulations applied when they were on the campus.
If they left the campus to go to Galveston or to Corpus Christi or somewhere, that was between them and the legal authorities.
There was the term double jeopardy that students used to say that
They went downtown and got drunk and got put in jail.
They paid a fine and got out of jail.
That ought to be it.
But old regulations provided that when you answered to the civil authorities, you had to answer to the university as well.
A violation in town was a violation of university regulations.
And when I first went there,
We dealt with students, their conduct off campus as well as on campus.
We were required to by the regulations, but then it was determined and decided that surely that was not our area.
We wanted them to be good citizens.
We wanted them not to violate the law, but we didn't want to dictate
to them that much about their private lives.
So that was a relief to get out of that.
Yet, as I said earlier, you give up something, you get something, and you give up something.
You get that freedom and you give up a certain amount of protection and buffering and so on that
well-meaning, compassionate staff member at the University College of the University can provide.

Some of the, I think some of the greatest members I have about my association with students at the University is where someone's student has touched my life or I've touched somebody's life and it became a, it's become a
a lifetime feeling and a relationship that exists.
You don't tell students what to do and what they can do and what not to do, but you share with them some thoughts of what might happen if you do this and what might happen if you do that.
And many students appreciate it.
There was one student that came in the store when we were down at Buda in the antique store
And I heard his voice, and I thought, George, I believe I've heard that voice before.
And after a while, I said, I think I know you.
He said, yes, Dean Franks.
He says, you suspended me from the university.
I said, I did.
And I said, OK. Now I know what it was about.
He had forged a letter to the Dean of Arts and Sciences
his friend who had gone, he belonged to the Hare Krishna organization.
There was funny looking haircuts and maybe a long flowing kind of a robe.
They've shown pictures of him at the airports and other places like that.
But anyhow, she'd gone to a national meeting and he forced a letter to the dean that she was
Her grandmother died, and she'd gone on to be with her grandmother.

Well, it was found out that she hadn't done that, and he was brought before me, and he admitted to forging the letter, and I had sold it, and I said, well, I can take you to a committee and let you plead your case before a committee, or I'll offer you suspension from the university for a year.
He said, well, I'll take the suspension from the university.
So he signed a piece of paper.
And I said, well, are you still associated with the organization?
He said, no.
I was on the West Coast.
I had a district out there in Oregon or Washington somewhere.
He represented the organization in that area.
Had a national meeting in New York.
And he went to New York.

He'd met his mother and dad there, and they had dinner together, and he was having a night meeting that night, and so he said his dad looked at the watch and said, Son, you'd better go now if you're going to make your meeting.
He said, I'm not going.
And then he went ahead and told me that his folks had pleaded with him to get out of the organization, but had given up on him.
and getting out of the organization.
They were just going to go ahead and love him anyhow, but he saw that he shouldn't be doing that.
He should get out of the organization.
Well, that was that kind of a personal relationship that you can establish with a student, even when you're disciplined.
The discipline itself should have some, I'll use such a word as curative value, it should have some value.
And of course it can be misused, and I'm sure I made some mistakes in some of the decisions I made relative to students.
But I would be a strong advocate for the schools,

college and university, having rules and regulations that are fair, apply to all students equally, but the expectations are such that when you come to be a part of us, you're going to give up some of your freedom that you have if you're just out in the community doing your own thing.
You have to have requirements about grade point average.
And of course, the professors usually do the determination about attendance in class.
Some professors say, three absences and you're out.
Some fellows say, six absences and you're out.
And some people say, don't miss my class unless you're sick.
So in the classroom, there's a
a lot of freedom for the professor to make decisions such as that.
But academic freedom doesn't grant the freedom to be wrong, whether it's the dean or the professor, or whatever it is.
Well, I guess that in local parentage business, parents bring their young
college students to the university with the expectation that there's going to be somebody there that'll kind of help look after them.
And maybe that that's just an old throwback that's still lingering with me.
I saw 31 freshman classes in the universities.
I participated in many of the orientation programs.
And to this day, I forget how excited and scared
parents and the students are when they start at the university.

Whether you remember some of your own experiences, the university is a big old world, you know, and you need somebody that will show an interest, offer some guidance and counseling and information that will make them feel at home.
feel comfortable.
Well, we still need colleges and universities that have organizations and staff members that are there to try to help the student wade through the academic waters, social and academic.
Much freedom we can't afford them, but with some guidelines
Okay, now if you would, discuss any of the Pacific protest movements that you remember.
Yes, I just thought about another one.
There was an incident that took place up on the campus resulting from some trees being prepared to take down on the campus.
make room for an addition to the Memorial Football Stadium.

The university administration and the regents had done some studies about whether to move the stadium off of the campus or to enlarge it in its present location, and it was decided that it would be best to enlarge the capacity of it right there on the campus.
And in order to do that, the trees along Walla Creek, many trees, had to come down.
And as soon as word was out that the trees had to come down in order to make room for the stadium, several individuals and groups, and I suppose that the Students for Democratic Society could be
given the credit for organizing a protest there.
It didn't have to be them, it could have been any of the students who were interested in saving the trees.
Anyhow, the protest was planned.
The day came when the trees were to come down.
My staff and I were there to observe what was going on.
heard the bulldozers as they cranked up.
We saw the students as they placed their bodies between the bulldozers and the trees.
We saw other students who climbed the trees.
Most of them were talked down, helped down from the trees by the university police, but one little girl got up
how up and out on a pretty good size limb, and was just balancing herself up there.
And the police tried to talk her into coming down, but she wouldn't come down.
So one of the university policemen climbed the tree with a rope and tied it around the young woman's waist and brought her down safely and sound.
And Mr. Irwin had been, I guess, on the scene pretty early.
He was there by the time I got there, and I was there pretty early that morning.
He was directing what was going on.
He was telling the bulldozers which trees to get next.
And so there was a great deal of scampering around.
came to me and said, is that Mr. Irvin over there?
And I said, yes.
He says, it's all right if I go and talk to him.
I said, I'm not taking appointments for Mr. Irvin.
So he went and visited with Mr. Irvin a little bit, and then he came back just as angry as he could be.
He said, you know what he said to me?
And I said, no, what did he say?
I told him I didn't think those trees ought to come down, and he told me in no uncertain terms and with a little profanity, he didn't give a damn what I thought.
So the trees came down, some of them pushed over, and most of the people, many of the people had walked away at this time, but enough
People stayed around to get, oh, I don't know, three or four pretty good-sized trees and dragged them by hand up on the campus and propped them up on the steps of the main building.
And there was a meeting going on inside of the president and some of his staff and maybe some of the regents.
I don't know exactly who was in that.
My staff member and good friend Ed Price was on the inside of

the meeting, observing what was going on up there, and I was working the outside, and he heard somebody say that, uh, I want those, uh, I want those people that brought those trees up there arrested and put in jail.
And the, Dr. Hackerman was our president at that time, and Dr. Hackerman stood up and had an envelope in his hand, and he laid it down on the, uh,
desk and said, gentlemen, I don't want those students arrested.
And they said, if they are arrested, go help bring in the trees up to the steps.
This is my resignation in this envelope right here.
Well, they didn't get arrested.
And so the president didn't have to tender his resignation.
But I thought it was a great show of courage
on the part of the president to say, don't want him arrested.
Matter of fact, that I saw the administration lean over backwards several times to keep from just grabbing somebody up, hauling off the campus under arrest.
And there was a
Maybe I mentioned the sit-in in the truck wagon where the tires were sliced.
I think I mentioned that.
But I believe those incidents involving a considerable number of students and non-students and whomever wanted to participate.
And I have to say that there were a number of faculty members
that were in sympathy with the movements that the SDS organization was advocating that moved to make some changes in university policy and regulation.
And some of them were faithful in their attendance at demonstrations, whether it was at the Pink Lounge or whether it was
downtown for a street demonstration.
They were taking part in it.
I guess if you were to study and analyze a little bit the organization of a university, you've got people all the way from one end of the continuum to the other, from left to right.
liberals and conservatives, and some radicals.
And I guess as a professor at Indiana said, and then the university said one time in class, they said, well, we've got some kooks here.
Every university campus has some.
But it takes a few kooks to keep the rest of us straight.
Well, kooks is not a good word.
It's a negative word.
But it takes people.
People don't have to hold the same ideas to get along.
As a matter of fact, the university is a place to be exposed to a lot of different philosophies and ideas.
And so I'm thinking about it after what, 20-some years, I reckon.
And my thinking may not be as clear
as it was when I left the campus.

But I left with a good feeling that I'd had the experience of being associated with a university of that size, of its magnitude in academic programs and activities, and there was a great spirit that permeates the campus.
Many of the people that were protesting in the 60s and 70s are now the executives in business and professional organizations.
I believe that's all about them, that I have to say.
And I can't think of any other large incident
You're trying to.
